                  <span class="classification-badge" style="margin-bottom:0.625rem;display:inline-flex;">KEY DERIVATION</span>
                  <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:1.25rem;color:var(--color-gold);margin:0;">
                    PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA256
                  </h3>
                </div>
                <div
                  style="
                    font-family: var(--font-mono);
                    font-size: 2rem;
                    font-weight: 700;
                    color: var(--color-gold);
                    white-space: nowrap;
                  "
                >600,000</div>
              </div>

              <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;max-width:680px;">
                Password-Based Key Derivation Function 2. Transforms your master password into a 256-bit cryptographic key by running it through HMAC-SHA256 in a tight loop — 600,000 times. Each iteration depends on the last. You cannot skip iterations. There is no shortcut.
              </p>

              <!-- Why 600k -->
              <div
                style="
                  background: rgba(255,215,0,0.04);
                  border: 1px solid rgba(255,215,0,0.12);
                  padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
                  margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
                  border-radius: 2px;
                "
              >
                <p
                  style="
                    font-family: var(--font-mono);
                    font-size: 0.75rem;
                    color: var(--color-gold);
                    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
                    text-transform: uppercase;
                    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
                  "
                >// WHY 600,000 ITERATIONS?</p>
                <p style="font-size:0.9rem;margin:0;">
                  OWASP 2023 recommends a minimum of <strong>600,000 iterations</strong> for PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA256. This reflects the current cost of GPU-based brute-force attacks. At 600k iterations on modern hardware, a single password trial takes approximately <strong>0.3–0.8 seconds</strong>. An attacker testing 1 billion passwords would need over 9 years on a single GPU. IronDome meets the current standard — and future releases will increase this as hardware improves.
                </p>
              </div>

              <!-- Code block -->
              <pre class="code-block" style="overflow-x:auto;"><span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># Key derivation — irondome/crypto.py</span>
key = PBKDF2HMAC(
    algorithm=hashes.SHA256(),
    length=32,            <span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># 256-bit output</span>
    salt=salt,            <span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># 32 random bytes, stored in salt.bin</span>
    iterations=600_000,   <span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># OWASP 2023 minimum</span>
).derive(master_password.encode())
<span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);">
# Salt is unique per installation — same password on two machines
# produces completely different derived keys. This is intentional.</span></pre>
            </div>

            <!-- Fernet / AES-256 -->
            <div
              class="tactical-card tactical-corners"
              style="padding:2rem 2rem 2rem 1.75rem;border-left:3px solid var(--color-green);"
            >
              <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;justify-content:space-between;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
                <div>
                  <span class="classification-badge classification-badge--green" style="margin-bottom:0.625rem;display:inline-flex;">SYMMETRIC ENCRYPTION</span>
                  <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:1.25rem;color:var(--color-green);margin:0;">
                    Fernet — AES-256-CBC + HMAC-SHA256
                  </h3>
                </div>
                <div
                  style="
                    font-family: var(--font-mono);
                    font-size: 1.25rem;
                    font-weight: 700;
                    color: var(--color-green);
                    white-space: nowrap;
                    text-align: right;
                  "
                >Authenticated<br />Encryption</div>
              </div>

              <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;max-width:680px;">
                Fernet is a high-level symmetric encryption scheme that wraps AES-256-CBC with HMAC-SHA256 message authentication. The critical property: it provides <strong>authenticated encryption</strong>. An attacker who modifies ciphertext cannot decrypt it — the HMAC will fail first. This prevents tampering, padding oracle attacks, and bitflip attacks simultaneously.
              </p>

              <!-- What Fernet includes -->
              <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(200px,1fr));gap:0.75rem;margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
                {[
                  { label: "Algorithm", value: "AES-256-CBC" },
                  { label: "Authentication", value: "HMAC-SHA256" },
                  { label: "Key size", value: "256 bits" },
                  { label: "IV", value: "Random 128-bit per op" },
                  { label: "Format", value: "Self-describing token" },
                  { label: "Tamper detection", value: "Yes — always" },
                ].map((item) => (
                  <div
                    style="
                      background: rgba(52,211,153,0.04);
                      border: 1px solid rgba(52,211,153,0.12);
                      padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
                      border-radius: 2px;
                    "
                  >
                    <div
                      style="
                        font-family: var(--font-mono);
                        font-size: 0.6875rem;
                        color: var(--color-text-muted);
                        text-transform: uppercase;
                        letter-spacing: 0.1em;
                        margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
                      "
                    >{item.label}</div>
                    <div
                      style="
                        font-family: var(--font-mono);
                        font-size: 0.875rem;
                        color: var(--color-green);
                        font-weight: 600;
                      "
                    >{item.value}</div>
                  </div>
                ))}
              </div>

              <pre class="code-block" style="overflow-x:auto;border-left-color:var(--color-green);"><span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># Fernet token structure (what gets written to disk)</span>
Version    | 0x80           <span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># 1 byte  — protocol version</span>
Timestamp  | uint64 BE      <span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># 8 bytes — when encrypted</span>
IV         | random bytes   <span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># 16 bytes — unique per write</span>
Ciphertext | AES-256-CBC    <span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># variable length</span>
HMAC       | SHA256         <span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># 32 bytes — covers ALL fields above</span>
<span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);">
# If HMAC does not verify → decryption NEVER starts.
# You cannot learn anything about the plaintext by probing.</span></pre>
            </div>

            <!-- System Key / Hardware Binding -->
            <div
              class="tactical-card tactical-corners"
              style="padding:2rem 2rem 2rem 1.75rem;border-left:3px solid #3b82f6;"
            >
              <div style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
                <span
                  class="classification-badge"
                  style="margin-bottom:0.625rem;display:inline-flex;background:rgba(59,130,246,0.08);border-color:rgba(59,130,246,0.3);color:#3b82f6;"
                >HARDWARE BINDING</span>
                <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:1.25rem;color:#3b82f6;margin:0;">
                  System Key — Machine-Specific Second Layer
                </h3>
              </div>

              <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;max-width:680px;">
                The vault is encrypted twice. The derived key (from your password) is one layer. The system key is the second — derived from hardware identifiers unique to your machine: CPU serial, motherboard UUID, machine hostname, and OS-level user identity. These are hashed together with a salt and passed through PBKDF2 to produce a 256-bit system key.
              </p>

              <div
                style="
                  background: rgba(59,130,246,0.04);
                  border: 1px solid rgba(59,130,246,0.15);
                  padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
                  margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
                  border-radius: 2px;
                "
              >
                <p
                  style="
                    font-family: var(--font-mono);
                    font-size: 0.75rem;
                    color: #3b82f6;
                    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
                    text-transform: uppercase;
                    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
                  "
                >// WHAT THIS MEANS FOR AN ATTACKER</p>
                <p style="font-size:0.9rem;margin:0;">
                  Stealing the vault file gives an attacker nothing. They also need your master password. But even with your master password, they need the exact hardware it was created on. The vault is <strong>physically bound to your machine</strong>. Copy the file to a different computer — it won't open. This is not copy protection. This is a security property.
                </p>
              </div>

              <pre class="code-block" style="overflow-x:auto;border-left-color:#3b82f6;"><span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># Hardware identity construction</span>
hardware_id = sha256(
    cpu_serial +
    motherboard_uuid +
    hostname +
    os_user
)

system_key = PBKDF2HMAC(
    algorithm=hashes.SHA256(),
    length=32,
    salt=hardware_salt,   <span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># separate from password salt</span>
    iterations=600_000,
).derive(hardware_id)

<span style="color:var(--color-text-muted);"># Final encryption key = combine(derived_key XOR system_key)
# Both must be correct to decrypt. Either alone is useless.</span></pre>
            </div>

          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

